Tutorial 5

Guideline for rounding off

  • Limit rounding off to the final answers. Rounding off in your working steps may reduce accuracy of your final answers.
  • If the answer is greater than 1, round off to 2 decimal places.
  • If the answer is less than 1, round off to 3 significant numbers.
  • When rounding, also take note of the natural rounding points, for example, costs in dollars would round off to 2 decimal places.

Where necessary, check the distribution for the variables and for the presence of outliers.

Tutorial 5 Part 2 (To be submitted - 30 Marks)

Context: Use data(‘smoke’). This is an actual data set with 807 observations on 10 variables. Data is collected from male individuals in 1979 and early 1980 from the Smoking Supplement to the 1979 National Health Interview Survey conducted in US.

The variables are described below:

  • educ: years of schooling
  • cigpric: cigarette price (in cents/pack) within the state the individual resides in
  • white: =1 if race is white; =0 if race is non-white
  • age: in years
  • income: annual income, $
  • cigs: cigarettes smoked per day
  • restaurn: =1 if restaurants in the individual’s state of residence has smoking restrictions; =0 if no smoking restrictions
  • lincome: log(income)
  • agesq: age^2
  • lcigpric: log(cigprice)

You are tasked to conduct the required analyses to better understand smoking behavior (or cigarette demand) in the US during the period of study. We will consider those who smoke zero cigarette per day to be a non-smoker while those who smoke at least one per day to be a smoker.

data(smoke)

Q2.(b) Amongst white individuals, the population proportion that is a smoker is said to be equal to 0.4. Evaluate if this statement is true by conducting a hypothesis test using 5% level of significance. Clearly define H0 and H1 and explain your findings. (4 marks)

SK_white <- SKi %>% filter(white ==1)

###H0: u = 0.4 v.s. H1: u != 0.4 where u represents the population proportion that is a smoker amongst white individuals.--> Conduct test at 5% significance level 
SK_white_smoke <- SK_white %>% filter(smoker=='Smoker')
phat <- nrow(SK_white_smoke)/nrow(SK_white)

critical_val <- qnorm(0.025)
critical_val
## [1] -1.959964
#critical value = -1.959964
test_stat <- (phat-0.4)/sqrt(0.4*(1-0.4)/nrow(SK_white))
test_stat
## [1] -0.8126006
#test statistic = -0.8126006

#Does test_stat fall above upper limit?
test_stat > -critical_val
## [1] FALSE
#Does test_stat fall below lower limit?
test_stat < critical_val
## [1] FALSE
p_value<- 2*pt(test_stat, nrow(SK_white))
p_value
## [1] 0.4167199
#Is p-value < 0.05 to reject H0?
p_value < 0.05
## [1] FALSE

For testing using critical value: We do not reject H0 because the test statistic falls outside of the rejection region. Thus, the statement is true. For testing using p-value: We do not reject H0 because p-value is more than 0.025. Thus, the statement is true.

END: YOUR ANSWER

** You are not required to remove any outliers detected**

######i cigs - mean, median, sd, kurt, skew
SK.cigs <- round(describe(SK$cigs),2)

######iii 95% confidence level for mean 'cigs' 
t <- qt((1-0.025),df =nrow(SK)-1)
deviation <- t*(SK.cigs$sd/sqrt(nrow(SK)))
mean <- SK.cigs$mean
lPI.cigs <- mean - deviation
uPI.cigs <- mean + deviation
cbind(round(lPI.cigs,2), round(uPI.cigs,2))
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,] 7.74 9.64

Type your answer here. ii. Distribution of cigs is positively skewed. Thus the data is not normally distributed. One outlier where 1 person smokes between 70 to 80 cigarettes per day.
iii confidence interval: 8.686493 +- 0.948126 –> [7.738367, 9.634619]. As 10 is outside the range of this confidence interval, we cannot conclude that the mean is 10.

Q2.(d) Dashboard for cigpric (4 marks)

    1. Develop the 99% prediction interval for cigpric. Explain what the interval tells us.
#Check normality 
plot(density(SK$cigpric),main="Density plot for Cigarette Price") #slightly left-skewed 

qqnorm(SK$cigpric,ylab="Sample Quantiles for Cigarette Price")
qqline(SK$cigpric,col="red")

shapiro.test(SK$cigpric)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  SK$cigpric
## W = 0.9279, p-value < 2.2e-16
#Based on visual inspection and values from shapiro test, we can infer that the data for cigpric deviates from normality. 
SK.cigprict <- transformTukey(SK$cigpric,plotit=TRUE)

## 
##     lambda      W Shapiro.p.value
## 585    4.6 0.9846       1.624e-07
## 
## if (lambda >  0){TRANS = x ^ lambda} 
## if (lambda == 0){TRANS = log(x)} 
## if (lambda <  0){TRANS = -1 * x ^ lambda}

t <- qt((1-0.005), df = nrow(SK)-1)
sd <- sd(SK.cigprict)
deviation <- t*(sd*sqrt(1+1/nrow(SK)))
mean <- mean(SK.cigprict)
lPI.cigpric <- mean - deviation
uPI.cigpric <- mean + deviation
print(cbind(lPI.cigpric, uPI.cigpric), digit=4)
##      lPI.cigpric uPI.cigpric
## [1,]    29618772   294590604
#reverse transform:
#y = x**lambda --> y = x**4.6 --> x = y**(1/4.6)
lPI.cigpric <- (mean - deviation) ^(1/4.6)
uPI.cigpric <-(mean + deviation)^(1/4.6)
print(cbind(lPI.cigpric, uPI.cigpric), digit=4)
##      lPI.cigpric uPI.cigpric
## [1,]        42.1       69.36

Type your answer here. 99% prediction level: [42.1, 69.36].

END: YOUR ANSWER

Q2.(e) Use the data to test if the mean number of cigarettes smoked per day is higher for individuals who are from states where restaurants have smoking restrictions versus those from states where restaurants do not have smoking restrictions. Conduct the appropriate hypothesis test and explain your conclusion from the results. Be sure to state your H0/H1 clearly, defining any symbols or notations you use in your hypothesis. (4 marks)

#To test H0 : u1<=u0 vs H1: u1>u0 where u1 is the mean number of cigarettes smoked per day for individuals who are from the states where restaurants have smoking restrictions while u0 is the mean number of cigarettes smoked per day..restaurants do not have smoking restrictions

#Two sample test for means with independent samples --> use t-test 

t.test(cigs~restaurn, alternative ="less",data=SK)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  cigs by restaurn
## t = 2.7161, df = 398.48, p-value = 0.9966
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group 0 and group 1 is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##      -Inf 4.454742
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 0 mean in group 1 
##        9.370066        6.597990
#this is because in the test H1 is H1: u0 - u1 <0[u0<u1] and our H1 is H1: u1<u0

Type your answer here. As the p-value = 0.9966 > 0.05 at 5% significance level, we have insufficient evidence to reject H0 and thus cannot conclude that the mean number of cigarettes smoked per day is higher for individuals who are from states where restaurants have smoking restrictions versus those from states where restaurants do not have smoking restrictions.

    1. Start by creating a variable, called agegp which will have 3 values: 1- for age less than 30; 2- for age 30 to 48; 3 - for age greater than 48. This variable defines the three age groups that we will compare in part ii. (1 mark)
    1. Create a table to display the frequency distribution for agegp. (1 mark)
    1. Conduct the appropriate hypothesis test to assess if the mean number of cigarettes smoked per day is same across people of three age groups. Be sure to state your H0/H1 clearly, defining any symbols or notations you use in your hypothesis, and explain your conclusion from the results.(5 marks)
######i create agegp
SKfi <- SK %>% mutate(agegp = ifelse( age<30, 1 , ifelse(age<49, 2, 3)))

######ii table

#More than 2 samples so we use ANOVA  --> but assumption need to be checked

#To test H0: u1 = u2 = u3 vs H1: at least 1 u is different from the others
#u1 is the mean no. of cigs smoked per day by someone in age category 1(<30 ), u2 for age category 2(30-48), u3 for age category3(>48)

###check normality

#Sample sizes are not equal. Check if equal variance assumption is met.
fligner.test(cigs ~ agegp, SKfi)
## 
##  Fligner-Killeen test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  cigs by agegp
## Fligner-Killeen:med chi-squared = 3.4464, df = 2, p-value = 0.1785
#Since p-value=0.1785 >0.05,we cannot reject the assumption that variances for the no. of cigs are equal. Based on this result, we proceed to conduct ANOVA test.

#conduct ANOVA#
SKfi$agegp <- as.factor(SKfi$agegp)
aov.cigs <- aov(SKfi$cigs ~ SKfi$agegp)
summary(aov.cigs)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)

Type your answer here. Based on the anova test, as p-value= 0.1785 > 0.05, we have insufficient evidence at 5% significance level to reject H0. Thus,we can conclude that the mean number of cigarettes smoked per day across the 3 age groups is not significantly different from one another.
